The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Kitchen accident chars bus 
                                                                                                               Kitchen accident chars bus 
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	A bus that ferried Left Front supporters from Burdwan to the Maidan on Sunday was gutted in a fire sparked by three rallyists cooking in the vehicle.         
	The blaze started around 12.40pm, when the bus (WB 41C 9240) was parked on St Georges Court Road  a no-parking zone within the 3km radius of Victoria Memorial where open fires are banned.        
	The owner of the bus  one of three who were cooking chicken curry on a stove  sustained serious injuries in the mishap.         
	The bus was gutted and the legs of the owner, 42-year-old Aparesh Chowdhury, were badly burnt, said an officer of Maidan police station.         
	The three said that the stove on which they were cooking burst. Chowdhury was sitting in front of the stove while they other two were preparing salad at the other end of the bus. They sustained minor injuries, added the officer.        
	Over 20 buses and trucks were parked nearby. Rally participants were cooking on stoves in those vehicles too, said witnesses.         
	Chowdhury was rushed to SSKM Hospital and was admitted to the burns ward. His condition is stable, said another officer.        
	We have started a case against the bus owner on charges of negligence and violating the high court order, said Partha Pratim Mukherjee, the officer-in-charge of Maidan police station.         
	The fire triggered panic among the thousands who were on their way to Brigade Parade Ground.         
	There could have been a stampede. We rushed to the spot and alerted the fire brigade, added the officer-in-charge.                                                                                                                                                                           
